299. From the abuse showered upon slaves Leonidas passes to the punishment inflicted on them, and extracts a jest from that too. A slave who was to be flogged was tied up, infr. v. 564, v. 617, Trin. 247. To prevent his kicking a weight was attached to his feet. If the weight was heavy enough

to keep him quiet he might be said to be in a state of equipoise. Hence Leonidas who has hung up Libanus says that he knows by experience what his weight is, be· cause he knows what weight was required to keep him quiet, or to continue his own metaphor, ‘to balance’ him. ν nudum, i.e. stripped for flog- m . g 150. expendi, ‘weighed you,’ i.e. sastened you up to the bearn.
